Since you’re on Wayland and already have wl-clipboard installed, you're in the right place. The command you're looking for is wl-copy.

To put the entire contents of a file onto your clipboard, use the following syntax:

Bash
wl-copy < path/to/your/file.txt
Pro Tips for wl-copy
The Pipe Method: If you're already doing something in the terminal and want to capture the output, just pipe it:
cat file.txt | wl-copy

Handling Images: One of the coolest features of wl-clipboard is that it isn't just for text. If you want to copy an image file to paste into Discord or GIMP, it detects the MIME type automatically:
wl-copy < screenshot.png

Clearing the Clipboard: If you copied something sensitive and want it gone:
wl-copy --clear

Quick Reference Table
Goal	Command
Copy File Content	wl-copy < filename
Copy Command Output	`ls -la
Paste to Terminal	wl-paste > newfile.txt
Paste to Stdout	wl-paste
Note: Since you're on Arch, make sure your environment variable XDG_SESSION_TYPE is actually set to wayland. If you ever hop back into an X11 session, wl-copy won't work, and you'd need xclip or xsel instead.

